From the retrieved content, we can analyze the reasoning behind inverting the learnability score in AJEST. On Page 10, the text states:

> "In JEST they use Eq. (1) to prioritize extremely difficult samples that are only easy to learn for a high-capacity reference [8]. This learnability score is therefore designed for situations in which a larger pre-trained model with good performance is available to use it as the smaller learner model’s teacher. Karras et al.’s research was framed on a different situation, one in which we do not count with a different, better pre-trained model, but with a 'bad version' of the learner model instead: a copy of the learner model with restricted capability [18]. We therefore hypothesized that it may be necessary to invert the sign of the learnability score, using Eq. (6) to compensate for the guide not being more capable than the learner."

This indicates that the inversion is specifically intended to compensate for the fact that the guide (a copy of the learner model with restricted capability) is *not* more capable than the learner. In other words, if the guide is less capable, then samples that are easy for the guide might actually be *difficult* for the learner — and thus, these samples should be prioritized as hard for the learner. Hence, inverting the learnability score aligns the selection mechanism with the actual difficulty for the learner.

This matches option B: “The inversion compensates for the guide being less capable than the learner, so that samples easy for the guide are prioritized as difficult for the learner.”

<answer>B</answer>
============================================================
