From the retrieved page (Page 29), Equation (15) defines the mean pairwise overlap as:

$$
M_{\text{iou\_overlap}} = \frac{1}{N_{\text{pairs}}} \sum_{p<q} \text{IoU}(B_p, B_q)
$$

where $ N_{\text{pairs}} = \binom{N_{\text{bboxes}}}{2} $, which is the number of unordered pairs of bounding boxes. This means that as the number of bounding boxes $ N_{\text{bboxes}} $ increases, the denominator $ N_{\text{pairs}} $ grows quadratically ($ \sim N^2 $).

The numerator is the sum of IoU values over all pairs. While more bounding boxes can lead to more overlapping pairs, the mean is computed by dividing the total sum by the number of pairs. If the additional boxes are randomly distributed or have low overlap, the average IoU tends to decrease due to the quadratic growth of the denominator. High $ M_{\text{iou\_overlap}} $ indicates occlusion and crowding, implying that the average overlap is sensitive to the density of bounding boxes.

Thus, as the number of bounding boxes increases, the mean pairwise overlap typically decreases because the number of pairs grows quadratically, diluting the average overlap.

<answer>A. It decreases because the number of pairs grows quadratically, diluting the average overlap.</answer>
