This equation defines the rotation error $\Delta\hat{\mathbf{R}}$ as the arccosine of a normalized trace expression. The numerator $\text{trace}(\hat{\mathbf{R}}^\top \mathbf{R}) - 1$ is a standard formula used to compute the cosine of the angle between two rotation matrices. Specifically, for two rotation matrices $\hat{\mathbf{R}}$ and $\mathbf{R}$, the quantity $\text{trace}(\hat{\mathbf{R}}^\top \mathbf{R})$ equals $1 + 2\cos\theta$, where $\theta$ is the angle between them. Subtracting 1 gives $2\cos\theta$, and dividing by 2 yields $\cos\theta$. Taking the arccosine then gives the angle $\theta$, which represents the rotation error.

Thus, the mathematical purpose of the expression $\text{trace}(\hat{\mathbf{R}}^\top \mathbf{R}) - 1$ is to measure the cosine of the angle between the estimated and ground-truth rotation matrices, which is then inverted via arccos to obtain the actual angle.

